# Modular Domain-Driven Architecture

## Caminhos neste repositório

O `tsconfig` mapeia `@/*` para `./src/*`. Código de aplicação fica em `src/` (`app/`, `shared/`, `modules/`). Config e `public/` permanecem na raiz do projeto.

## Core Principle

Every feature belongs to a module. Every module represents a domain.

The domain is the unit of ownership. Nothing crosses domain boundaries without an explicit, intentional contract.

## Directory Structure

```
src/                    # opcional — pode ser omitido (pastas na raiz)
  modules/
    auth/
      features/             # user-facing capabilities — ver regra feature-sliced
        login/
          ...
          index.ts
        reset-password/
          ...
          index.ts
      components/           # shared across features of this module only
      hooks/                # shared across features of this module only
      services/             # shared across features of this module only
      store/                # module-level state shared across features
      types/                # module-level types shared across features
      index.ts              # public API — only export what other modules may consume
    payment/
      features/
        checkout/
          ...
          index.ts
        refund/
          ...
          index.ts
      components/
      hooks/
      services/
      store/
      types/
      index.ts
    <domain>/
      features/
        ...
      ...
      index.ts
  shared/               # truly cross-domain primitives (UI kit, http client, i18n)
  app/                  # app shell — routing, providers, composition root
```

> The internal structure of each module follows Feature Sliced Design (regra **feature-sliced**). Every user-facing capability is a feature folder under `features/`. Loose files at the module root exist only to share code across features of the same module.

## Rules

### 1. One module = one domain
- Each folder under `modules/` (ou `src/modules/`) represents exactly one business domain (e.g. `auth`, `payment`, `billing`, `catalog`, `user`, `notification`).
- Do not create modules named after technical concerns (`utils`, `helpers`, `common`) — those belong in `shared/` if truly generic.

### 2. Public API via `index.ts`
- Every module exposes a single `index.ts` as its public contract.
- External code may only import from `modules/<domain>/index.ts`, never from internal paths like `modules/payment/services/stripeService.ts`.
- Internal module files are private by convention.

### 3. No cross-domain direct imports
- A module **must not** import directly from another module's internals.
- If module A needs something from module B, it must be exported through `modules/B/index.ts`.
- If two modules repeatedly depend on the same primitive, extract it to `shared/`.

### 4. Shared is not a dumping ground
- `shared/` is for infrastructure and UI primitives only: design system components, HTTP client, config, i18n, date utils.
- Business logic never lives in `shared/`. If it has domain meaning, it belongs in a module.

### 5. New feature = identify the domain first, then the feature
- Before creating any file, identify which domain owns this feature.
- If it belongs to an existing domain, add it inside that module under `features/<feature-name>/`.
- If no existing domain fits, create a new module with a clear domain name.
- Never place feature code loose at the module root — it always goes inside a `features/` subfolder.
- The internal structure of every feature follows the **feature-sliced** rule.

### 6. Store / state is scoped to the module
- State management (Zustand slice, Redux slice, React context) lives inside the module that owns the data.
- Cross-domain state sharing is done by consuming the public API, not by merging slices.

### 7. Services / API calls are inside the module
- All API calls related to a domain live in `modules/<domain>/services/` (or feature-level `services/` per feature-sliced).
- No API call logic in components or hooks outside the owning module.

## Naming Conventions

| Layer | Convention | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Module folder | kebab-case | `payment`, `auth`, `user-profile` |
| Component | PascalCase | `PaymentForm.tsx` |
| Hook | camelCase with `use` prefix | `usePaymentStatus.ts` |
| Service | camelCase | `paymentService.ts` |
| Type file | camelCase | `payment.types.ts` |
| Public export | Named exports in `index.ts` | `export { PaymentForm }` |

## What to Check on Architecture Changes

When touching folder structure or module boundaries, verify:

- [ ] The new file lives inside the correct domain module
- [ ] The new file lives inside a `features/<feature-name>/` subfolder, not loose at the module root
- [ ] No internal path is imported from outside the module
- [ ] `index.ts` is updated if a new public export is needed
- [ ] Shared code in `shared/` has no domain-specific logic
- [ ] No circular dependencies between modules
- [ ] The feature's internal structure follows the **feature-sliced** rule

## Examples

**Correct**
```ts
// modules/checkout/hooks/useCheckout.ts
import { createPayment } from 'modules/payment'   // via public index.ts ✓
import { getCurrentUser } from 'modules/auth'      // via public index.ts ✓
```

**Wrong**
```ts
// modules/checkout/hooks/useCheckout.ts
import { stripeService } from 'modules/payment/services/stripeService'  // internal path ✗
import { authStore } from 'modules/auth/store/authStore'                 // internal path ✗
```
